This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it deals with the improvement of automated dialogue systems for customer support service. It also involves natural language processing techniques for the selection of negative responses. 

It could also belong to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as it involves the development of automated dialogue systems. 

cs.LG (Machine Learning) is another likely sub-category as the proposed approach involves the selection of negative samples based on the distribution of responses in the train set, which is a machine learning technique. 

cs.IR (Information Retrieval) is also a possible sub-category as the paper deals with the retrieval-based dialogue system quality. 

Finally, cs.SD (Sound) is a less likely sub-category as the paper does not seem to involve any sound-related research.
